                 IN MODERN PHYSICS



Many of the concepts of physics which were erroneous or
     unexplainable due to lack of a counterpart in experience have been
         explained and clarified by the operational philosophy.


                                                             By WALTER        MRUK


  Modern physics begins about 1900. Before
that year Newton's Principia had so satisfac-
torily considered  dynamical situations   that
further development along these lines seemed im-
possible. In fact, what we have come to consider
as classical physics is built upon the structure
set up by Newton.
  At the beginning of the century, however, dif-
ficulties arose in trying to develop a suitable
model to describe atomic systems with classical
physics. To add to these difficulties, the prob-
lem of adequately describing (mathematically)
X-rays, radioactivity, blackbody radiation, the
photoelectric effect, and the specific heat of solids
led to conclusions which were not only ambiguous,
but also completely without a counterpart in ex-
perience. For example, the classical equations
describing the radiation of heat energy from a
body at a given temperature held for the long
wave components of the radiation and agreed
rather well with experiment. On the other hand,
for the short-wave components of radiation, the
classical equations failed entirely. Whereas ex-
perience shows that the intensity of the radiation
reaches a maximum value at a definite wave
length (or frequency) and then decreases, the
classical equations claim that the radiation in-
tensity not only fails to reach a maximum but
also increases indefinately as the frequency in-
creases, going, in fact, as the square of the fre-
quency.
  Numerous other such catastrophes added to the
haze enveloping the physics frontier. Such para-
doxes as the Michelson-Morley experiment, which
was designed to detect a relative motion between
the ether and the earth, led to ad-hoc descriptions
-descriptions which were supplied to account
only for a given paradox. In due time, the need
for a revamping of the basic ideas and concepts
of physics became necessary, and demanded the
attention of the great physicists. One of the first
of these physicists was Max Planck. It was Planck
who first proposed (1900) the daring hypothesis


of the quantum theory when he was able to ex-
plain the black-body spectrum in terms of as-
sumed emission and absorbtion of elecgromagne-
tic radiation in discrete quanta. Each quantum
consisted of an amount of energy equal to a con-
stant (which is now appropriately called Planck's
constant) multiplied by the frequency of the ra-
diation in question. The quanta were supposed
to fly through space with the velocity of light
like a hail of shot. Particular conditions were
established under which a system could emit or
absorb the quanta and these conditions accounted
for the black-body radiation very well.
  Einstein in 1905 went even further than Planck.
Not only did he incorporate Planck's quantive
hypothesis, but also insisted that such properties
were inherent in the nature of radiation itself.
There exist a series of experiments which the
classical wave theory is scarcely capable of de-
scribing but which are readily intelligible from
the Einstein standpoint.   Perhaps the most
straightforward of these is the protoelectric ef-
fect, which states that when suitable radiation is
made to impinge upon a metal surface in a high
vacuum, the surface is observed to become posi-
tively charged. One way for the surface to be-
come so charged is by the emission of photoelec-
trons (or electrons). With suitable apparatus,
these electrons can be captured and will thereby
yield current. The velocity of the electrons can also
be measured appropriately . On classical grounds,
certain predictions were made concerning the
relation between the intensity and frequency of
the incident light source, the velocity of the
emerging electrons, and their number. Yet ex-
perience showed that these predictions were not
at all true. By means of the quantum theory,
however, all the classical shortcomings were re-
moved.
