  Killing power of a bullet is dependent on three
things; kinetic energy, penetration, and expan-
sion. The kinetic energy of a bullet when it
reaches its target is a function of the mass of
the projectile and its velocity at that point, and
may be represented by the familiar formula;
   KE=I/2L UVt       Penetration of a bullet is
directly proportional to the weight and velocity
of the bullet and inversely proportional to the
effective resistance or density of the target body.
  Several factors are responsible for the expan-
sion of a bullet. First and most important is the
velocity with which the projectile strikes the
target. At high velocities the impact received
when entering the target body causes an expan-
sion or upsetting of the nose of the bullet which
is better known among ballisticians as mushroom-
ing. Another important factor which contributes
to the mushrooming of a bullet is the centrifugal
force acting on the periphery of the projectile.
This centrifugal force is produced by the rotation
of the bullet, the rotation being received by the
rifling of the gun barrel, and causes expansion to
proceed in a radial direction. It is interesting to
note that the speed of rotation is also governed
by the velocity of the bullet as it passes through
the bore. For argument's sake, assuming a con-
stant bullet weight, killing power is primarily
determined by bullet velocity.
  In rifles today, velocities above 4,000 feet per
second are not unusual, but because of their in-
herent design revolvers are limited as to these
ultra-high bullet velocities. This natural handi-
cap typical of revolvers impairs their ability to
equal rifles in terms of killing power. However,


special bullets such as hollow points, when used
in revolvers greatly increase their killing power
and wound producing ability. Unfortunately,
unless these bullets are driven at very high velo-
cities, they are incapable of expanding or mush-
rooming properly. At this point it may be well to
define high velocities with respect to revolvers.
With the exception of the .357 Magnam cartridge
and revolver it is difficult and dangerous to pro-
duce bullet velocities in excess of 1,000 feet per
second in revolvers.
  Realizing these limitations, the author has en-
deavored to design a revolver bullet which will
perform efficiently and destructively at velocities
as low as 800 feet per second.
  For a bullet to expand properly at these low
velocities something other than an ordinary hol-
low-point bullet is desired. By adding the lack-
ing velocity energy in a form of potential energy
the desired mushrooming and expansion of the
bullet is obtained. This is accomplished by the
use of an explosive charge in the nose of the bul-
let. "What," you may ask, "an explosive bullet?"
Exactly. The idea is nothing new but when ap-
plied to a revolver bullet it produces amazing re-
sults. This type of explosive bullet is capable of
terrific expansion and can produce wound cava-
ties superior in many respects to those made with
some high power rifles!
  All bullets used in the development were hand
cast in a Keith hollow-point mold block using a
special plug desig aed to enlarge the hollow-point
cavity to the proper dimensions in order to receive
the explosive charge and its components. Bullets
were cast from an alloy of I part tin to 20 parts
lead and were sized to a diameter of .358 of an

