The explosive charge itself consisted of three
separate components; a cap or primer, an anvil,
and the explosive powder charge.     Aluminum
tubing 5/32 of an inch in diameter was used as
the anvil to detonate the cap and formed the con-
tainer for the powder charge. The primer cap,
of the small percussion pistol type, was slipped
over one end of the anvil and the tube was then
filled with Hercules Bullseye powder. Powder
charge averaged 1.3 grains by weight. The as-
sembled unit was then pressed into the bullet
cavity until seated on the bottom of the cavity.
When properly seated, the cap was slightly lower
than the rim of the bullet nose. This raised rim
served as a safety precaution to prevent detona-
tion of the charge in case the finished cartridge
is accidentally dropped on its nose. The rim of
the bullet nose was then crimped in slightly by
bringing an ogive die down over the bullet. This
crimp holds the explosive components in firmly
and prevents their jarring loose from the recoil
when in the chambers of the revolver. After
these operations were completed, the bullet was
ready for loading in the cartridge case and that
procedure was the same as for any other bullet.
Figure 1 shows the bullet components and a cross
section of the finished bullet. The finished bullet
weighed 145 grains and propelling powder charges
were developed from standard loading tables
using this weight bullet.
   Since there was no way of knowing just how
rapid an acceleration the bullet could stand be-
fore exploding in the gun barrel, it was decided
to proceed with the utmost caution to prevent this
possible danger. Several cartridges were loaded
and fired in succession. Each successive bullet
was fired with an increase in velocity over the
previous ones. Bullet velocities were increased
from 100 feet per second to 950 feet per second
and slightly over. Two bullets were fired at each
separate velocity. The first ones contained only
the cap and anvil. The second contained cap,
anvil, and powder. These progressive tests were
all fired from behind the protection of a large
piece of 1/4 inch steel armor-plate, lest an ex-
ploding bullet wreck the gun. The handgun used
in the development and testing of the "OPX"
(Open Point Explosive) bullet was a standard
Smith and Wesson .38 Special military and police
revolver with a 6 inch barrel.


