By PROF. R.C. GORHAM


  Modern civilization finds it neces-
sary to regulate the practices of per-
sons whose activities deal with the
protection  of human     life, health,
rights and property. The professions
of medicine, law and engineering are
primarily intrusted with the respon-
sibility incident to such activities.
The elimination and exclusion, as
matters of public welfares, of the dis-
honest and unqualified from the prac-
tice of these professions are unde-
batable tenets.
  The first engineering registration
law was established for the District
of Columbia. During this time engin-
eering registration came to the United
States, laws have been enacted in
each state, and today every state,
territory, possession, and district of
the nation has a statute defining and
governing the practice of engineer-
ing. There are some 400,000 engin-
eers in the U. S. A., while some
160,000 are registered under these
laws. Certainly the time will soon
come when the entire profession will
be registered.
   While engineering registration laws
derive their primary justification from
considerations of public safety and the
protection of public interest, they are
also necessary for the protection of
the good name of the profession and
it's standing in public confidence.
Registration laws make it possible to
(1) stop the practice of engineering
by the unqualified; (2) stop the mis-
appropriation and abuse of the desig-
nation engineer; (3) oust from the
ranks of professional engineers those
who prove themselves to be unworthy
and incompetent; (4) preserve for the
worthy engineer his rights of prac-
tice against restriction, encroachment
and unqualified competion. A Penn-
sylvania court recently ruled that a
person holding himself out to be an
engineer, but not registered, has no
standing in a court of law attampting
to force payment for his services. The
court, in fact, ruled that the services
of the non-registrant had been illigal-
ly rendered contrary to the pihibiic
policy of the state as declared by 1f.i
legislature.
   The term "professional engineer"
 Within the meaning and intent of
 Pennsylvania Act No. 367, page 2 (d)
 "means an individual licensed and
 registered under the laws of this
 Commonwealth to engage in the prac-
 tice of engineering."


  Briefly the term "practice of en-
gineering" means any professional
service or creative work requiring en-
gineering education, training, and ex-
perience and the application of spe-
cial knowledge of the mathematical.
physical and engineering sciences to
such professional services or crea-
tive work as consultation. investign
tion, evaluation, planning, design, and
supervision of construction for the
purpose of assuring compliance with
specifications and design, pertaining
to any private or public utilities,
structures, buildings, machines, equip-
ment, processes, works or projects.
  In general, the requirements for
registration as a professional engin-
eer emphasize character. education
experience, and the passing of pre-
scribed examinations. Three succes-
sive steps are required in most states,


