   Members of engineering registra-
tion boards are Professional Engin-
eers of high standing, nominated by
their Professional colleagues in each
state; their service is one of devotion
to the Profession, self sacrificing and
non-lucrative. There is no inducement
to make the appointments a political
consideration. Examinations, registra-
tions and revocations are all handled
by boards of examiners. Cases of un-
lawful practice are decided in court.
Therefore, the administration of the
registration law is kept on as high a
plane as the standards of the Profes-
sion itself.
   Registration has been used by other
professions as a powerful instrument
for raising educational qualifications,
electrical standards; Professional sta-
tus, and public recognition. It will do
the same for the engineering profes-
sion if the young graduate engineers
proceed at once to work at it to that
end. The ultimate goal is for all grad-
uate engineers to apply for the En-
gineer-In-Training certificate imme-
diately following their graduation, and
help prove to the lawmakers, officials
and the public that they mean busi-
ness in Engineering, which is a learn-
ed Profession.


