  Is the engineering training that we receive at
Pitt too theoretical? Probably many of us have
asked ourselves that question before and have
come up with an answer-yes. Perhaps there is
too much bookwork and not enough chance for the
individual student to investigate and work on a
practical problem or test of his own liking or
creation. Of course our lab work helps some, but
offers very little chance for individual study or
self-expression.
  However, it has been a long standing policy in
the Mechanical Engineering Department to en-
able all interested students to do some practical
work or research on a project of their own choos-
ing. It was for this purpose that the courses
M.E. 97 for Mechanicals and A.E. 97 for Aero-
nauticals were created. Here the student picks
the project that he wishes to work on, gains first
hand information and experience by working on
it, and also receives credits for his efforts. In
the case of the Aero students, this work can also


