            RALPH GIMERA AND
            WILLIAM KALASKI
  Since the advent of the gase turbine and jet
engine, engineers have been devoting much re-
search to the study of combustion factors which
affect the burning of fuels. Among their dis-
coveries was the fact that sound waves impressed
upon a flame could affect it in many ways. They
can set up the turbulence that is needed to get
proper combustion, but if left uncontrolled, they
can cause rough burning and even blowoff of the
flame. This discovery was found to be especially
useful in studying the effects of sounds set up in
jet engines upon the combustion characteristics.
   In one of the projects carried on by students
apparatus was built that could be used to deter-
mine the effects of sound waves upon the combus-
tion of a fuel. It is essentially a burner tube with
provisions made to impress a sound wave of up
to 30 KC upon the mixture to be carried to the
flame. Also provisions were made to measure the
air to fuel ratio and temperature of the mixture
as well as the temperature of the flame surface.
The effects will be determined by means of high
speed photography.
   The original design was done last year by Ralph
Gimera and last semester Bill Kalaski finished
the design and started construction. In the fu-
ture other students will complete the instrumen-
tation and calibration of the unit,
   In addition to its basic purpose, the apparatus
seems to be flexible enough for more general com-
bustion experiments such as basic tests on fuels,
mixtures, additives and flame propagation velo-
cities.
