employed are screens formed of color
phosphors arranged in patterns of
dots, lines and checkerboard. Al-
though the dot structure has been
adopted for the tri-color tube now
used experimentally in the RCA com-
patible color television system, other
designs can incorporate any one of
the several screen textures of varia-
tion of them without affecting the
system.
  The tri-color tube of the dot struc-
ture screen design reproduces color
pictures when color signals are broad-
cast, or it will produce black and
white pictures when the signal is in
standard black and white.
  On a black and white receiving
tube, or kinescope, the inside of the


face plate is covered with a solid coat-
ing of sensitive phosphorescent ma-
terial. In the tri-color tube the screen
assembly, or face of the tube, consists
of an aperture mask, spacer frame
and tri-color phosphor dot plate which
acts as the direct view color screen.
  The dot plate is flat glass on which
600,000 small closely spaced phosphor
dots, each .014 inches in diameter,
are arranged in triangular groups.
Each group consists of three dots
which glow in the three primary
colors when hit by a scanning elec-
tron beam.
  Behind the phospher dot plate is
the aperture or shadow mask. This is
a thin metal sheet perforated with
200,000 tiny holes, one for each tri-
angular color group, that acts as a
mask so that, in scanning, each elec-
tron beam can "see" only one dot
of each color group. The mask is kept
at the correct distance from the phos-
phor dot plate by means of a spacer
frame.
  In the neck of the tube are the
three electron guns which generate
the beams for scanning the phosphor
dot plate.


