BERYLLIUMt


The many properties which may easily be realized from beryllium
       copper make it a leader among the non-ferrous metals.


  How would you feel if you had to replace the
radiator in your care every year?  No doubt
you would complain endlessly. But you don't have
to replace your radiator every year. In fact you
should never have to replace it. Why? Because
copper is the material used for your radiator. If
ordinary steel were used there would be the yearly
replacements.  The corrosion resistant copper
radiator usually out lives your car. This is only
one example where a non-ferrous material gets
the nod over steel. Because of the varied proper-
ties obtainable from non-ferrous metals, these
materials have been developed to meet many of
industry's specialized needs. The development of
beryllium copper is a good example. In 1931
beryllium copper was first produced commercial-
ly in the United States. At that time, this alloy
was so rapidly and highly publicized that the re-
sult was a misunderstanding of its properties and
a consequent failure of the material for the uses
to which it was applied. Since then, however, the
alloy with development and proper application
has become a valuable commercial product. Its
high strength and hardness, excellent corrosion,
wear, and fatigue resistance, along with good
electrical and thermal conductivity have resulted
in the wide application of beryllium copper. It
is most familiar as a spring material but has be-
come popular for use as bushings, bearings, cams
and elements in precision instruments. The de-
velopment that has made this wide application
possible is the heat treating technique that brings
out the optimum physical properties of this age
hardening alloy.
   Copper and small percentages of beryllium
form a partial solid solution type alloy. A copper
alloy of two percent beryllium, for instance, is a
single phase, solid solution structure in the range
13850 to 1650' F. At room temperature, under
equilibrium conditions, the structure consists of
two phases, the solid solution phase rejecting a
second phase upon equilibrium cooling. However,
if the alloy is cooled very rapidly, as in a water
quench, from the solid solution field, this single
phase structure is preserved at room temperature.
The structure at room temperature is then con-
sidered a super saturated solid solution. In beryl-
lium copper this single phase condition will re-
main indefinitely if the temperature is not raised
appreciably.  Raising the temperature to the
range 600' to 9000 F. and holding causes the solid
solution, tending toward equilibrium, to reject or
precipitate a second phase. These features of the
physical structure of beryllium copper are the
points that are significant in the alloy's heat
treatment. Proper control of these phenomena
results in a material with excellent properties.


  Quenching beryllium copper from the solid
solution temperature range results in a soft struc-
ture that is easily worked and formed, while sub-
sequent heating to the 600' to 9000 F. range and
holding hardens the material and brings out the
desired physical properties. This first step is
known as a solution anneal while the second treat-
ment is called age hardening. The desired pro-
perties of the material determine the manner in
which these operations are carried out. The
significant factors in each operation will be dis-
cussed.
          SOLUTION ANNEALING
  The two main factors that must be considered
for proper solution annealing are time and tem-
perature. What temperature should be employed
and how long should the alloy be soaked at this
temperature? Time and temperature are im-
portant because they control the grain size of the
structure and the completeness of solubility of
the beryllium in the copper. Complete solubility
with small grain size is desired. Higher soaking
temperatures and longer time periods are 'sug-
gested for best solution effect. However, these
conditions promote grain growth. A compromise
in time and temperature is the usual adoption.
  John T. Richards, development engineer for the
Beryllium Company, suggests a solution anneal
for a typical high strength 2% beryllium alloy
(25 alloy) of one hour per inch or fraction of
inch of section thickness at 1450' F. A water
quench from this temperature is the general prac-
tice.
              AGE HARDENING
   As in solution annealing, the basic factors con-
sidered in artificial age hardening are time and
temeprature. Again it should be emphasized
that the particular properties desired in the hard-
ened material determine the hardening practice.
The effect of the time and temperature variables
can most easily be illustrated by reference to fig-
ure #1, showing the relationship of tensile
