and aging time at various temperatures. Of sig-
nificance is the fact that as temperature of treat-
ment is increased the time factor becomes critical.
That is, at the high temperatures the maximum
tensile strength is obtained quickly but also drops
off quickly. The decrease in tensile strength is
known as "over aging." Although the lower tem-
perature treatments require longer aging periods
the maximum tensile strength is higher and the
over aging effect is more easily avoided. Effect
of cold working the solution annealed material
prior to aging is clearly shown by comparing part
(a) and (b) of figure one. The cold working
raises the maximum tensile strength and de-
creases the aging time required to reach this max-
imum. Of course, the cold working gives the alloy
an initially higher tensile strength.
   There are two types of hardening treatments
in general use. According to Richards they are
the standard low temperature type and the short
time, high temperature type. The processes vary
depending upon whether a high strength alloy or
a high conductivity alloy is desired. If the high
strength alloy is desired by the standard low
temperature process, Richards suggests a com-
position of greater than one per cent beryllium
held for one to three hours at 6000 to 650' F. For
a high conductivity alloy a composition of less
than one percent beryllium, held for one to three
hours at 850' to 9000 F is recommended. The
high temperature process is not applied to high
conductivity alloys, but for a high strength alloy,
Richards recommends holding for fifteen to nine-
ty minutes at 6500 to 7250 F. These suggested
practices should be considered only as a guide.
   The properties desired determine the treat-
ment. This might best be seen by referring to
figure two. As Richards points out, each treat-
ment has its advantages. If good resistance to
wear is desired, thirty minutes heating time
(number one) will result in maximum tensile
strength and hardness. For maximum stability,
which is desirable in spring applications, a forty-
five minute hold, which will result in minimum
drift is specified (number two). For dimension-
al control, the heating time should be sixty min-
utes (number three), so that the tension modulus
is a maximum. Bear in mind, though, that these
times apply only for an aging temperature of
6600 F.
   Clearly then, the value of beryllium copper
 stems from its responsiveness to heat treatment.
 Its many uses depend upon the properties obtain-
 able by particular heat treatments. These treat-
 ments are simple to apply and can be depended
 upon to give consistant results. As industry is


