   Today, nearly all manufactured parts receive
careful inspection, and it is essential that these
parts be inspected through the use of non-de-
structive methods. This inspection coordinates
surface appearance, tolerance limitations and
composition rquirements. An equally important
requisite of structures to most inspectors is the
character and homogeneity of the composite sec-
tions. There is an ever increasing desire to see
and to know what lies below the surface of the
metal object. The exacting service requirements
of machine parts and the necessity of weight
limitations has made it imperative that these
parts be of a uniform high quality. In the past,
most of the non-destructive inspection has been
done with the X-ray machine, but in 1930 the
Navy used radium as its source emaninating
gamma-rays for the first commercial radiograph-
ic examination. The sternpost of the cruiser
"Chester" was examined. Today, because of such
advantages as constant activity, simplicity of op-
eration, portability, minimum of scattering and
good penetration, radium radiography proves
more practical than the X-ray machine in many
cases.
  What is a radiograph? It is a photographic
record of the passage of X-rays or gamma rays
through an object onto a film. The diagram in
Figure 1 shows the essential features in the pro-
duction of a radiograph. The focal spot is a small
capsule containing the radium salt which is used
as the source of radiation. The radiation pro-
ceeds in straight lines to the object; some of the
rays pass through and others are absorbed--the
amount transmitted depending on the nature of
the material and its thickness. If the object is a
steel casting, for example, and a void, which was
formed by a gas bubble, exists, more radiation
will pass through the section containing the void
than through the surrounding area because the
void results in a reduction of the total thickness
of steel to be penetrated. A dark spot, corres-


the non-destructive testing of castings.


ponding to the projected position of the void, will
therefore appear on the film when it is developed.
Thus, a radiograph is in reality a shadow picture
of an object-the dark regions on the film repre-
senting the more penetrable parts, and the lighter
regions the more opaque.
  Photographic films are sensitive to the direct
action of the x-rays, but the exposure time neces-
sary may be decreased very appreciably by the
use of a fluorescent chemical, e. g., calcium tung-
state, in contact with both sides of the film. Such
a powdered chemical is mixed with a suitable
binder and coated on cardboard to form an inten-
sifying screen. Its action depends upon the fact
that it converts some of the X-ray energy into
ordinary light to which the film is also very sen-
sitive.
  In order that a radiograph may be of maximum
usefulness in determining the homogeneity of the
object inspected, it should have four characteris-
tics: it should be free from distortion or deforma-
tion of the shape of the object; it must contain a
sharp and well defined shadow of the object;
there must be sufficient contrast in the darkening
of the film to permit its interpretation; it must
be free from chemical stains, misleading process
markings, or abrasions.
