attitude toward nature. Herein lies the great
genius of Einstein. It was due to his work on the
photoelectric effect, the specific heat of solids,
and relativity that the modern physicist had to
retreat and take stock, so to speak, of his funda-
mental attitude toward nature in order to avoid
another mental revolution such as the one per-
perated by Einstein. In effect, the modern physi-
cist wishes to remove the necessity of another
Einstein by formulating a basic attitude which is
entirely flexible to new situations, for another
mental revolution, besides being costly, would
prove very embarrassing.
   The fruit of the Einstein revolution is that it
has produced what has become known as the
operational philosophy. True, this philosophy
has its origin in the works of Ernst Mach as
logical positivism and Einstein was greatly influ-
enced by Mach's writings, but the fact remains it
was Einstein who formulated much of the basic
principles in his work on relativity.
   In the first place, the operational philosophy
demands that the attitude of the physicist be one
of empiricism. The limits on new experience be-
came infinite and experience is determined solely
by experience.    Previously, physical concepts
were defined in terms of their properties so that
physics assumed an abstract character in analogy
with mathematics as is evident by Newton's three
laws of motion where one begins with a given set
of axioms and postulates and proceeds from there,
not caring whether or not any conclusions which
result have actual physical meaning or a counter-
part in nature, as long as the basic axioms and
postulates are not violated. It was the task of
the physics experimenter to ascertain whether
the concepts as defined orginally actually had a
counterpart in nature and all too frequently no
counterpart existed. Consequently, the new atti-
tude which arose through the operational philo-
sophy and is completely flexible to new concepts
and experiences insists that the concept be syn-
onomous with a given set of physical operations.
These defining operations must be unique in
order to remove any possibility of ambiguity in
practical experience; therefore, the physicist
readily admits the possibility of new kinds of
experience outside the realm of his present know-
ledge, but he is now mentally geared for whatever
facts present themselves.
  As defined by Halliday, the main features of
the operational philosophy can be stated as:
  1) Concepts are not considered as things in-
tuitively understood; concepts are defined as the
objective results of certain carefully prescribed
operations that can, at least in principle, be car-
ried out in the laboratory.
  2) These operational definitions give rise to
sets of pointer readings of one sort or another.
Such pointer readings are the "irrefutable facts
of nature".   Quantities for which operational
definitions cannot be given are unobservable;
they do not belong to the realm of science.
  3) Physical laws are relationships between
operationally defined physical quantities that al-
ways seem to occur when certain experiments are
performed.
  4) It is the role of theory to give, on the basis
of a few hypotheses, a simple unified description


of as many experiments as possible. The question
of the ultimate truth of either hypotheses or
theory simply does not arise.
   5) Theories and hypotheses may be replaced
at any time by more useful ones; that is by ones
that describe the same experiments in a simpler
way. In point of fact, many scientists identfy
"reality" with the economy with which a logical
positivist describes the sense perceptions that
come (or can be made to come) within his ex-
perience.
   To appreciate the beauty of the operational
philosophy an example of its application will now
be considered. A basic concept fundamental to
physics is that of length. The question arises as
to what we mean by Ingth. Since we admit the
operational philosophy, the question of what is
length can be rephrased as, "What are the opera-
tions which define length?". In the case of mea-
suring concrete objects familiar to everyday liv-
ing, such as a room in a house, the operations in-
volved in measuring the length of the room con-
sist essentially of taking a yardstick (or other
length measuring device), laying it on the floor so
that one end of the measuring stick coincides
with one end of the room, marking the floor at
the point where the other end of the measuring
rod terminates, then proceeding from the new
mark in a similar fashion until the entire room
has been covered from one edge to the other, and
stating that the length of the room is the number
of times the measuring rod was laid along the
room edge. On this basis, it would seem that the
operations defining the length of the room have
been uniquely determined. However, in the case
of measuring the distance from the earth to the
moon or to any of the stars, a breakdown in the
operational definition occurs. To measure the
distance from the earth to the moon according to
our definition requires an observer to take a
measuring rod and to apply it in the same manner
as when measuring the room. Up to this time,
such a procedure seems indeed impractical; con-
sequently, a revision of the original definition
seems necessary. But must the original defini-
tion be revised? In fact, what is meant by the
statement, "The moon is 285,000 miles away from
the earth"? It means that light beams have re-
placed the previous measuring rods; that by the
methods of trigonometry and angle measurement,
the distance to the moon has been calculated. The
trigonometric methods employed assume that Eu-
clidean geometry applies to very great distances,
but this assumption itself has been open to ques-
tion for some time. The measurement also as-
sumes that Newtonian mechanics is valid at such
great distances, and it is further assumed that the
light beams can indeed be unequivocally substitut-
ed for the original measuring rod. In effect then,
the direct concept of length has developed into an
entirely different complex concept of length, and
to remain completely rigorous on the grounds of
the operational philosophy, this new length should
be called by another name. The operations in-
volved here differ radically from the original de-
fining operation and could justify a new name.
