   Another interesting ramification of the opera-
 tional definition concerns meaningless questions.
 As stated earlier, unless a unique set of operations
Sdefines a quantity, it is labeled unobservable, or
what is the same thing, meaningless, and there-
fore does not belong to the realm of science. One
question which has occurred to most people can be
stated somewhat as, "Is the sensation which
registers in my mind as blue the same sensation
of blue which registers in the mind of my neigh-
bor?" The answer to this question must, of
course, be reducible to a set of operations where-
by the sensations registered by the two indivi-
duals may be conclusively compared.
   It is readily observed that much daily conver-
sation reduces itself to such meaningless state-
ments and questions. The modern physicist must
be continuously aware of the dilemma of mean-
ingless questions as he pursues his thoughts down
new avenues. Obviously the operational philoso-
phy gives him a foothold from which to operate.
  A final interesting ramification of the opera-
tional philosophy concerns the spiritual or reli-
gious. Unless one can perform operations upon
a world which may exist entirely apart from the
real physical world about us, the question of a
spiritual world remains outside the realm of
science; consequently, the age-old "battle" be-
tween science and religion, as viewed from the
operational viewpoint, really does not exist.
   The host of physical laws which the modern
physicist uncovers places him in the class of the
artist except that the two are diametrically op-
posed in motivation. For where the artist wishes
to particularize a general concept such as an
emotion or beauty in a painting, drama, or musi-
cal composition, the physicist wishes to reduce the
myriad of observable physical phenomena to gen-
eral principles. They are alike in that each uses
constructs and inventions to accomplish hs end.
And this must be born in mind when the physicist
announces his discoveries-that he is dealing
with constructs and inventions by means of which
he uncovers relationships between operationally
defined physical quantities that seem to occur al-
most invariably. These relationships constitute
the essence of modern physics development; they
are labeled physical laws.
  By means of the new attitude resulting from

