tional organization with professional and
student chapters throughout the country,
could provide them with such benefits. Many
of the professional members of this Society
are industrial engineers.
   The Society of Industrial Engineers had
been founded to promote and develop the
principles of that profession, while the Tay-
lor Society had been organized to forward
the concept of "Scientific Management" as
developed by Frederick Winslow Taylor. A
third organization, the Industrial Methods
Society, merged with the S.A.M. in 1946.
Thus, the S.A.M. is an expanding and active
organization, well-represented in the field
of industrial engineering. The professional
and student chapters in Pittsburgh are
among the Society's largest and most active.
Many projects, conferences, and other events
are held by the student chapters at both Pitt
and Duquesne University. The Pittsburgh
professional chapter, representing the in-
dustrial center of the nation, is very power-
ful within the national organization, and
some of the country's largest firms, business,
and industries are represented by its mem-
bers.
