INK FROM THE EDITOR'S PEN


   With registration six weeks behind us, and
the second semester now in full swing, spring
fever and the forthcoming baseball season team
up to make calculus, thermo, and TAM more dif-
ficult than ever. But if the student in Engineer-
ing or Mines can manage to overcome these ob-
stacles and still have a little ambition left, he will
find spring the season of golden opportunities.
   The most golden of these opportunities are the
 conventions which are so popular in March, April,
 and May. These conventions cover all phases of
 engineering and give any student who attends a
 chance to do a good turn for himself as well as
 his school. First, much is to be learned by at-
 tending these conventions. It gives you an op-
 portunity to get out and see how the other half
 lives, for a tour of the host school's campus is
 always a part of the program. Here you will see
 what some other school has to offer in the way
 of labs, curricula, and campus activities. In the
 past, these tours have opened the eyes of many
 Pitt men who have either bragged or complained
 about the facilities here at Pitt. From the bull
 sessions between meetings you will learn how
 other schools function, and bring back ideas that
 will add new life to your own campus organiza
 tion and broaden its program.
   Second, it gives you a chance to represent your
school. A large turnout by a school will nuicklv
identify it as a "live wire outfit", as the Pitt men
who attended the AIEE convention at the Univer-
sity of Pennsylvania and the Pi Tau Sigma Con-
vention at the University of Kentucky last fall
found out.
  Unfortunately, some instructors have been
known to hold reviews for major tests or cover
material that the student can't get himself upon
finding that a large number of their students
have found a convention more important than
their class. These instructors are apparantly too
short sighted to see that their position as lecturer
or professor at our schools carries no more pres-
tige than the name of the school itself. and the
missing students are helping to build that pres-
tige. Fortunately these incidents are relatively
rare, and we can only hope that in the future
they will cease.


   The third and most important aspect of a con-
 vention is the prize paper contest which is almost
 always the climax. These contests give you a
 chance to bring back the bacon for your school,
 and to a much larger extent for yourself. By
 merely entering such a contest you will put your
 name on the program and your face before a
 group of men who both now and in the future are
 the big wheels in your profession, and establish
 yourself as a competitor who is not afraid of
 competition. When you win a prize, your name
 and possibly your picture will appear in a pro-
 fessional journal where students, professional
 engineers, and future employers will see them.
 To make matters even better, the competition in
 these contests is not nearly as tough as you think.
 That paper you had to write for English 39, with
 a little expansion and research, can do very well.
   Speaking of research, there is no call for com-
 plaint about lack of facilities. True, there is
 much room for improvement in our existing lab-
 oratories, and the class of 1960 will be much bet-
 ter equipped than the classes of 1952-55. But
 there are many existing facilities in our present
 labs that most students fail to realize. A glance
 at the articles in the January and present issue
 of this ,magazine should quickly convince all
 Chemical and Mechanical engineers of this fact.
 The Metallurgical Engineering laboratory located
 on the ground floor of State Hall is our most out-
 standing engineering laboratory, and one of the
 best met labs in the country. A glance at the Elec-
 trical Engineering labs in Thaw Hall should con-
 vince any man in that department of his oppor-
 tunities. The same is true of the other depart-
 ments. Unfortunately, some instructors have
 been known to discourage research on the part of
 the student, but if you really want to work and
 have something worthwhile in mind, you will not
 be stopped.
   You can't spare the time for research or for the
 conventions? You can if you start planning now.
 Since most conventions are scheduled near the
 weekend the most that you will miss is two days'
 classes, which is a reasonable investment con-
 sidering the large return. Start in now to make
 your spring semester a worthwhile experience!

